english:
  title: 'In Praise of Minister Choe''s Portrait: A Commendation on the Image of Choe Yeong, Minister of the Three Excellencies'
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the summer, fourth month, of the twelfth year of Hongwu, a royal messenger conveyed the sovereign's words: "Minister Choe Yeong of the Three Excellencies has served my late father with utmost devotion and righteous fervor, defending our realm from foreign invasion and preserving our peace to this day. I hold him in highest regard. Now his subordinates have painted the scene of his breaking the enemy lines at Hongsan, which we wish to transmit to all generations to come. You, Saek, shall compose a commendation for it."

    Your servant Saek humbly reflects: When the state employs its civil and martial ministers, some serve at the center as the sovereign's trusted counselors, nurturing the vital essence of the realm, while others stand at the borders as claws and fangs, wielding strength to repel foreign invasion. Thus do the people of the world fix their gaze upon these men, watching the fortunes of the age rise and fall. Yet those who venture forth as generals and return as ministers of state—whom the court relies upon as pillars of strength, whom the borderlands depend upon for peace, before whom crafty conspirators cower and flee, and at whose mere rumor distant bandits retreat—such men are rarely found. Among all of today, none stands forth more eminently than Minister Choe.

    The Minister of the Three Excellencies is none other than the Grand Commandant. Since the year of Gengyin, he has repelled invaders at the coastal reaches, routed foes across the Yellow River, quelled rebellion at Xingwang Temple, and commanded eighty-seven engagements great and small. Striking where enemies resist, piercing where they are hollow, meeting each desperate moment with cunning stratagem—yet though past sixty winters, his vigor remains undiminished. What but Heaven's gift of courage and wisdom could achieve this?

    The Minister's forebears advanced the realm through literary refinement, rising to the office of Prime Minister and serving as examiners of the civil service—achievements one could enumerate. Yet the Minister himself has devoted his talents to martial strategy, rising to extraordinary and mighty deeds in an age of tumult and calamity. Often he has brandished his spear whilst composing verse, his spirit commanding an entire generation. Moreover, his father taught him to regard gold as mere clay, and this teaching he has inscribed upon his heart. Thus his integrity of spirit has only deepened with age. The Minister embodies both the civil and martial virtues, uniting loyalty and filial piety in equal measure.

    How magnificent is our Sovereign's wisdom! Following the late king's noble intentions, he elevates virtue and repays merit, thereby awakening the keen and steadfast spirit needed to navigate these troubled times toward lasting peace. It is fitting that Minister Choe should receive such supreme and luminous favor. Alas, how splendid! Your servant Saek finds himself moved to dance with his hands and leap with his feet, his long praises flowing forth unbidden. Thus the verse reads:

    Brilliant and fearsome his renown,
    Steadfast his will, luminous his mind.
    The sea's brigands tremble in dread—
    He is the nation's rampart and wall.
    Local tyrants shrink and hide—
    He is the people's judge and guide.
    With seal of office and opened府 bestowed,
    Honor befits such service as his.

    Consider the Minister's heart:
    It mirrors his father's heart,
    Clear as ice in winter's grip,
    Bitter as the regrowth of felled trees.

    At towering Hongsan he raised his drum,
    His figure blazing midst the battle line.
    Heroic bearing, noble mien,
    His spirit swept across the realm.
    The painter captured his very likeness—
    All who gaze upon it stand in awe.

    Ancient wisdom speaks: "Virtue is subtle, beyond designation."
    Yet were we to designate it, to whom else but the Minister?
    May he endure in strength and vigor,
    Eternal guardian at our Sovereign's side.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Hongsan (鴻山): Site of a significant military victory by Choe Yeong against invading forces during the Goryeo-Joseon transition period.'
  - key: ''
    value: The year Gengyin (庚寅) refers to 1350 in the Goryeo chronology, marking the beginning of Choe Yeong's military service.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Three Excellencies' (三司) refers to a high ministerial position combining military and administrative authority.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to his father teaching him to regard gold as clay reflects the Confucian ideal of the incorruptible official who spurns material wealth.
